# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antiseptic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] The compound was discovered by Gustave Chancel in 1853 by fractional distillation of fusel oil.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] He measured its boiling point at 96°C, correctly identified its empirical formula, studied some of its chemical properties and gave it two names: **propionic alcohol** and **hydrate of trityl**.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] After several unsuccessful attempts, it was synthesized independently and by two different routes by Eduard Linnemann and Carl Schorlemmer in 1868.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Fusel alcohols like 1-Propanol are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of 1-Propanol are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] 1-Propanol shows the normal reactions of a primary alcohol.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Thus it can be converted to alkyl halides; for example red phosphorus and iodine produce n-propyl iodide in 80% yield, while PCl3 with catalytic ZnCl2 gives n-propyl chloride.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Reaction with acetic acid in the presence of an H2SO4 catalyst under Fischer esterification conditions gives propyl acetate, while refluxing propanol overnight with formic acid alone can produce propyl formate in 65% yield.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Oxidation of 1-propanol with Na2Cr2O7 and H2SO4 gives a 36% yield of propionaldehyde, and therefore for this type of reaction higher yielding methods using PCC or the Swern oxidation are recommended.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Oxidation with chromic acid yields propionic acid.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is manufactured by catalytic hydrogenation of propionaldehyde.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Propionaldehyde is produced via the oxo process by hydroformylation of ethylene using carbon monoxide and hydrogen in the presence of a catalyst such as cobalt octacarbonyl or a rhodium complex.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Other proposed industrial processes include the two-step isomerization and hydrogenation of propylene oxide.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] A traditional laboratory preparation of 1-propanol involves treating *n*-propyl iodide with moist Ag2O.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] 1-Propanol can also be prepared via the hydrogenation of acrolein with metal catalysts.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is thought to be similar to ethanol in its effects on the human body, but 2 to 4 times more potent according to a study conducted on rabbits.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Many toxicology studies find oral acute LD50 ranging from 1.9 g/kg to 6.5 g/kg (compared to 7.06 g/kg for ethanol).
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Effects include alcoholic intoxication and high anion gap metabolic acidosis.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] As of 2011, one case of lethal poisoning was reported following oral ingestion of 500mL of 1-propanol.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] Due to a lack of long term data, the carcinogenicity of 1-propanol in humans is unknown.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] 1-Propanol has a high octane number and is suitable for use as engine fuel.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] However, propanol is too expensive to use as a motor fuel.
[src:antiseptic/1-propanol] The research octane number (RON) of propanol is 118, and the anti-knock index (AKI) is 108.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] As an antiseptic, it is marketed as **S.T.37** by Numark Laboratories, Inc.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] (in a 0.1% solution) for oral pain relief and as a topical antiseptic.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] It is available for use topically on small skin infections or as an ingredient in throat lozenges.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] As an anthelmintic, 4-hexylresorcinol was sold under the brand Crystoids.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] Sytheon Ltd., USA markets 4-hexylresorcinol (trade named Synovea HR).
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] Johnson & Johnson uses 4-hexylresorcinol in its Neutrogena, Aveeno, and RoC skincare products as an anti-aging cream.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] 4-Hexylresorcinol has been used commercially by many cosmetic and personal care companies, such as Mary Kay, Clarins, Unilever, Murad, Facetheory, Arbonne, and many small and large companies.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] A study published in *Chemical Research in Toxicology* shows that 4-hexylresorcinol used as a food additive (E-586) exhibits some estrogenic activity, i.e. resembles action of the female sex hormone estrogen.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] However, a recent study published in *Applied Sciences* shows that 4-hexylresorcinol did not change the expression of estrogen receptor-α, -β, or p-ERK1/2 in MCF-7 cells.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] In an ovariectomized animal model, the 4HR group showed similar levels of ERα, ERβ, and prolactin expression in the pituitary gland compared to the solvent only group, while the estradiol group showed higher levels.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] Serum prolactin levels were similar between the 4HR and solvent only groups.
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] In one study, 4-hexylresorcinol increased the shelf life of shrimp by reducing melanosis (black spots).
[src:antiseptic/4-hexylresorcinol] In mice with cancer, 4-hexylresorcinol inhibited NF-κB and extended their survival rate.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] In aqueous solution 8-hydroxyquinoline has a pKa value of ca.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] 9.9 It reacts with metal ions, losing the proton and forming 8-hydroxyquinolinato-chelate complexes.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] The aluminium complex, is a common component of organic light-emitting diodes (OLEDs).
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] Substituents on the quinoline ring affect the luminescence properties.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] In its photo-induced excited-state, 8-hydroxyquinoline converts to zwitterionic isomers, in which the hydrogen atom is transferred from oxygen to nitrogen.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] 8-hydroxyquinoline was first obtained by Hugo Weidel and his student Albert Cobenzl in 1880.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] They decarboxylated so-called oxycinchoninic acid (from cinchonine) and characterized the resulting compound as melting at about 70°C.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] They identified that the hydroxy group is on the benzene ring (but not its particular place) and called the compound **oxyquinoline** and **α-quinophenol**.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the following year more chemists found other ways to make the compound.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] Zdenko Hans Skraup discovered a way to synthesize substituted quinolines from substituted phenols and described three isomers of oxyquinoline, identifying the structure of 8-hydroxyquinoline.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] Otto Fischer and his student Karl Bedall made the compound from a sulphonic acid independently at about the same time, but misidentified its structure.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] By 1888 azo dyes were made from the compound.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the 1920s insoluble chelates of 8-hydroxyquinoline were discovered.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] The complexes as well as the heterocycle itself exhibit antiseptic, disinfectant, and pesticide properties, functioning as a transcription inhibitor.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] Its solution in alcohol is used in liquid bandages.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] It once was of interest as an anti-cancer drug.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] A thiol analogue, 8-mercaptoquinoline is also known.
[src:antiseptic/8-hydroxyquinoline] The roots of the invasive plant *Centaurea diffusa* release 8-hydroxyquinoline, which has a negative effect on plants that have not co-evolved with it.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] An **antiseptic** (Greek: ἀντί, romanized: *anti*, lit.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] 'against' and σηπτικός, *sēptikos*, 'putrefactive') is an antimicrobial substance or compound that is applied to living tissue to reduce the possibility of sepsis, infection, or putrefaction.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Antiseptics are generally distinguished from *antibiotics* by the latter's ability to safely destroy bacteria within the body, and from *disinfectants*, which destroy microorganisms found on non-living objects.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Antibacterials include antiseptics that have the proven ability to act against bacteria.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Microbicides which destroy virus particles are called viricides or antivirals.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Antifungals, also known as antimycotics, are pharmaceutical fungicides used to treat and prevent mycosis (fungal infection).
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Antiseptic practices evolved in the 19th century through multiple individuals.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Ignaz Semmelweis showed already in 1847-1848 that hand washing prior to delivery reduced puerperal fever.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Despite this, many hospitals continued to practice surgery in unsanitary conditions, with some surgeons taking pride in their bloodstained operating gowns.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Only a decade later the situation started to change, when some French surgeons started to adopt carbolic acid as an antiseptic, reducing surgical infection rates, followed by their Italian colleagues in the 1860s.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] In 1867 Joseph Lister published seminal paper *Antiseptic Principle of the Practice of Surgery*, where he explained this reduction in terms of Louis Pasteur's germ theory.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Thus he was able to popularize the antiseptic surgical methods in the English-speaking world.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] Antiseptics can be subdivided into about eight classes of materials.
[src:antiseptic/antiseptic] These classes can be subdivided according to their mechanism of action: small molecules that indiscriminately react with organic compounds and kill microorganisms (peroxides, iodine, phenols) and more complex molecules that disrupt the cell walls of the bacteria.
[src:antiseptic/atc-code-a01] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QA01**.
[src:antiseptic/atc-code-a01] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
[src:antiseptic/atc-code-d08] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QD08**.
[src:antiseptic/atc-code-d08] ATCvet codes without corresponding human ATC codes are cited with the leading Q in the following list.
[src:antiseptic/atc-code-r02] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QR02**.
